oying any Ingress resources afterward. Since the current setup runs with a single replica and maxUnavailable is set to 1, the rolling update will cause a brief outage—I can either scale up to 2 replicas first to maintain availability during the update, or accept the downtime and run the upgrade during a quiet period, relying on the preStop hook to gracefully drain connections.\n\nI'm recommending Option A to scale to 2 replicas for zero-downtime. The execution plan involves patching the webhook's failurePolicy to Ignore so its own downtime doesn't block Ingress operations, then scaling the controller deployment to 2 replicas before proceeding with the image update.\n\nWriting kubectl commands... Verifying the demo namespace has the necessary Service and Ingress resources for the demo-app (currently missing), then checking the rollback procedure with the previous image digest stored for quick restoration if needed.\n\nBefore proceeding, there are several open items to confirm: the target version and digest, Kubernetes 1.35 compatibility, whether to use rolling updates or blue-green deployment, any ConfigMap key changes in the release notes, and scheduling a maintenance window if the blue-green approach is chosen — plus creating the demo-app Service and Ingress as a separate task outside this upgrade scope.\n\nNow I need to store the plan as a ConfigMap. The tricky part is handling the multiline text without escaping issues in the shell command. I'll write the plan to a temporary file first, then use `--from-file` to create the ConfigMap from that file, which is more reliable than trying to escape everything inline.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2780,"cache_read_input_tokens":41690,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2780},"output_tokens":18,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context